{"cursor":"13616","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nAn 'institution' is any structure or mechanism of social order and cooperation\ngoverning the behavior of a set of\nindividuals within a given community â may it be human or a specific animal one.\nInstitutions are identified with a social purpose, transcending individuals and\nintentions by mediating the rules that govern cooperative living behavior. [http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/social-\ninstitutions/ Stanford Encyclopaedia: Social Institutions]\n\nThe term \"institution\" is commonly applied to customs and behavior patterns\nimportant to a society, as well as to particular formal organizations of\ngovernment and public services. As structures and mechanisms of social order\namong certain species, institutions are one of the principal objects of study in\nthe social sciences, such as political science, anthropology, economics, and\nsociology (the latter being described by Durkheim as the \"science of\ninstitutions, their genesis and their functioning\"). Durkheim, Ãmile [1895]\n\"The Rules of Sociological Method\" 8th edition, trans. Sarah A. Solovay and John\nM. Mueller, ed. George E. G. Catlin (1938, 1964 edition), pp. 45\nInstitutions are also a central concern for law, the formal mechanism for\npolitical rule-making and enforcement.\n","linknr":353,"url":"Social_institution","recorded":1362476933,"links":61,"instances":["law","polity"],"pdf":["http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/picrender.fcgi?artid=1608780&blobtype=pdf"],"categories":["Economics terminology","Political science terms","Social institutions"],"headings":["Examples of institutions","Aspects of institutions","Perspectives of the social sciences","Institutionalization","See also","References","Bibliography","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/SNA_segment.png/180px-SNA_segment